SIMPLE: narrative
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Narrative
<hw>Nar"ra*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>narratif</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to
narration; relating to the particulars of an event or
transaction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Apt or inclined to relate stories, or to tell
particulars of events; story-telling; garrulous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But wise through time, and <qex>narrative</qex> with age.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Narrative</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Narrative
<hw>Nar"ra*tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which is narrated; the
recital of a story; a continuous account of the particulars of an event
or transaction; a story.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cyntio was much taken with my <qex>narrative</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tatler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Account; recital; rehearsal; relation; narration;
story; tale. See <er>Account</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Narratively</ent>⟦br⟧
